We see that most of the column names have changed. Now we will normalize all the data frame except y.yes from bankdummy df. Here 0 is no and 1 is yes Let us now normalize all the data. We will use min-max normalisation.

normalize <- function(x) { #developing min-max normalization function
return((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}
#normalizing bank data:
banknorm <- as.data.frame(lapply(bankdummy, normalize)) #using lapply to normalize every column
#To confirm all the data have worked properly:

1c: (20 pts) Build a classification model using a support vector machine that predicts if a bank customer will open a term deposit account.

So we will be developing support vector machine to predict y.yes we will be using the svm() function from library e1071(). Also, we will be using the column y.yes as factors for the output to be of the shape of 0 or 1.

library(e1071)
model_svm <- svm(as.factor(y.yes) ~ ., data=banknorm)
summary(model_svm)

1d: Build another classification model using a neural network that also predicts if a bank customer will open a term deposit account.

So now we need to use neural network. All the data has already been converted to numeric and normalized. So we will directly put the values in neural network:

library(neuralnet)
n <- names(banknorm)
f <- as.formula(paste("y.yes ~", paste(n[!n %in% "y.yes"], collapse = " + "))) #neuralnet() does not support the ~. notation. As a workaround, we use the as.formula and pass it to neuralnet()
set.seed(12345) #since neuralnet has randomized initialization, we set the seed.
model_nn <- neuralnet(f,data=banknorm,linear.output=F)
plot(model_nn)

Evaluating performance of neural network:

model_results <- compute(model_nn, testnorm[-43]) #we use compute() as predict() cannot be used here.
pa <- model_results$net.result
pred_nn <- ifelse(pa > 0.5,1,0) #converting all values above 0.5 to 1, else to 0.
tab1 <- table(pred_nn,testnorm$y.yes)
tab1
       
pred_nn    0    1
      0 3532  150
      1  468  371

So we see the accuracy with a single neural network is (3903/4521)*100 = 86.33%

Improving model performance: We can improve the model performance by increasing hidden layers. However, since the code will require significant run-time complexity, it is intentionally commented. However the code can be run faster if someone has gpu access.
